<span id="iv.vi.iv.xxxviii-p1"></span> <span id="page_550">p. 550</span>
<span id="iv.vi.iv.xxxviii-Page_550"></span><span class="c11"><span
id="iv.vi.iv.xxxviii-p1.1"></span>Chapter XXXVIII</span>.—*How the
Market-Town of Gaza was made a City for its Profession of Christianity,
and received the Name of Constantia.*

<span id="iv.vi.iv.xxxviii-p2"></span><span class="c11"><span
id="iv.vi.iv.xxxviii-p2.1"></span>For</span> in fact the place now
called Constantia, in the province of Palestine, having embraced the
saving religion, was distinguished both by the favor of God, and by
special honor from the emperor, being now for the first time raised to
the rank of a city, and receiving the more honored name of his pious
sister in exchange for its former appellation.

